    "text": "Read the raw signals, and this morning they're emphatic. Your HRV is 65 ms against a 30-day average of 55.4 — a big positive margin — and resting heart rate sits at 57 bpm, right in line with its usual 58. After a 64-minute run carrying a 16.3 load, that combination is exactly what bounced-back looks like: real leftover fatigue would show suppressed HRV and an elevated resting heart rate, and you have the opposite. Sleep backs it up too, 7.0 hours, matching your weekly rhythm. Without a composite score, HRV against your own baseline is the single most useful daily check, with morning resting heart rate as the tiebreaker. Today you're clear to train as planned.",
